<h2>1. Environment Setup</h2>
<p>These commands prepare RStudio with the necessary tools to handle air quality data.</p>

<ul>
<li><b>install.packages(c("openair","tidyverse","lares"))</b>: Downloads the external libraries from the internet.</li>
<li><b>library(tidyverse)</b>: Loads a collection of tools for data cleaning and transformation.</li>
<li><b>library(dplyr)</b>: Loads a specific part of Tidyverse used for manipulating data frames.</li>
<li><b>library(lares)</b>: Library used for mass text replacement and cleaning messy strings.</li>
<li><b>library(openair)</b>: Specialized package for air quality and wind analysis.</li>
</ul>

<h2>2. Data Import and Reshaping</h2>
<p>Raw pollution data often comes in a <b>wide format</b> (one column per hour).  
These commands convert it into a <b>long format</b> (one row per observation) which is required for plotting.</p>

<ul>
<li><b>city &lt;- read.csv("...")</b>: Downloads the raw CSV file and stores it in a variable named <i>city</i>.</li>
<li><b>pivot_longer(city, cols=c(h01...h24), names_to="hour", values_to="value")</b>: Converts the 24 hourly columns into two columns: hour and value.</li>
<li><b>city2 &lt;- city1[-c(1,2,4,6:16)]</b>: Removes unnecessary columns to keep the dataset clean.</li>
</ul>

<h2>3. Date and Time Formatting</h2>
<p>Computers treat dates as text unless we convert them into proper <b>time objects</b>.  
This step is essential for time-series analysis.</p>

<ul>
<li><b>mutate(date = paste0(data, " ", hour))</b>: Creates a new column combining date and hour.</li>
<li><b>replaceall(city2, ...)</b>: Cleans messy timestamp text and standardizes times.</li>
<li><b>as.POSIXct(city2$date, ..., tz="Europe/Madrid")</b>: Converts the date column into a proper datetime object.</li>
<li><b>as.factor(city2$pollutant)</b>: Converts pollutant names into categories for plotting.</li>
</ul>

<h2>4. Advanced Visualization (openair)</h2>
<p>These functions automatically generate environmental charts.</p>

<ul>
<li><b>timeVariation(city2)</b>: Shows pollution changes by hour, weekday, and month.</li>
<li><b>trendLevel(city2, pollutant="H2S")</b>: Creates a heatmap to identify long-term pollution trends.</li>
</ul>

